President Obama has announced his intent to nominate Thomas Countryman as Assistant Secretary for International Security and Non-Proliferation at the Department of State. Countryman is currently serving as Deputy Assistant Secretary for European and Eurasian Affairs at the Department of State. He has a long career in the Foreign Service, having served in various roles such as Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary for Political-Military Affairs and Foreign Policy Advisor to General James Conway. Countryman has also held positions at the U.S. Embassy in Athens, the Department of State, and the National Security Council.

President Obama also announced his intent to nominate Anne Wedner as a member of the United States Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy at the Department of State. Wedner has experience in marketing and previously worked at Heller Financial, CME, and Cramer-Krasselt. She is a former Foreign Service Officer and has served in Caracas, Venezuela, and Washington D.C. Wedner has a Master of Arts in Law and Diplomacy from the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University and an A.B. from Harvard University.